---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import HubCard from '../../components/HubCard.astro';
---

<DocsLayout
    title="Modern CSS Features"
    description="Modern CSS features and how they affect Layered Semantic CSS architecture."
>
    <section class="site-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Modern CSS</p>

        <h1>
            Modern CSS features
        </h1>

        <p class="intro">
            Modern CSS features reduce defensive selectors, heavy naming
            systems, and JavaScript-driven styling. Used well, they make LSCSS
            simpler and clearer.
        </p>
    </section>

    <nav class="section-nav" aria-label="Modern CSS sections">
        <a href="#start-with-these">Start here</a>
        <a href="#selector-tools">Selector tools</a>
        <a href="#layout-tools">Layout tools</a>
        <a href="#lscss-position">LSCSS position</a>
    </nav>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2 id="start-with-these">
            Start with these
        </h2>

        <div class="hub-grid">
            <HubCard href="/modern-css/where/" title=":where()">
                <p>
                    Use expressive selectors without adding specificity weight.
                    This is one of the safest modern CSS tools for architecture.
                </p>
            </HubCard>

            <HubCard href="/modern-css/has/" title=":has()">
                <p>
                    Style components based on their contents or state without
                    reaching for extra JavaScript hooks too early.
                </p>
            </HubCard>

            <HubCard href="/modern-css/container-queries/" title="Container queries">
                <p>
                    Make components respond to their container instead of the
                    viewport. This supports more portable UI patterns.
                </p>
            </HubCard>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2 id="selector-tools">
            Selector tools
        </h2>

        <div class="hub-grid">
            <HubCard href="/modern-css/is/" title=":is()">
                <p>Reduce selector repetition while keeping grouped patterns readable.</p>
            </HubCard>

            <HubCard href="/modern-css/not/" title=":not()">
                <p>Use simple exclusions without turning selectors into puzzles.</p>
            </HubCard>

            <HubCard href="/modern-css/nesting/" title="CSS nesting">
                <p>Keep related rules together, but avoid recreating deep selector chains.</p>
            </HubCard>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2 id="layout-tools">
            Layout and experience tools
        </h2>

        <div class="hub-grid">
            <HubCard href="/modern-css/logical-properties/" title="Logical properties">
                <p>Reduce left/right assumptions and improve support for different writing directions.</p>
            </HubCard>

            <HubCard href="/modern-css/view-transitions/" title="View transitions">
                <p>Enhance navigation and interface changes while respecting progressive enhancement.</p>
            </HubCard>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2 id="lscss-position">
            LSCSS position
        </h2>

        <p>
            LSCSS uses modern CSS to reduce architectural friction. The goal is
            not more abstraction. The goal is clearer, simpler CSS with fewer
            override battles.
        </p>
    </section>
</DocsLayout>
